 an oleaginous organism to create a strain with significant lipogenesis capability. Specifically, we rewire Yarrowia lipolytica's native metabolism for superior de novo lipogenesis by coupling combinatorial multiplexing of lipogenesis targets with phenotypic induction. We further complete direct conversion of lipid content into biodiesel. Tri-level metabolic control results in saturated cells containing upwards of 90% lipid content and titres exceeding 25 g l -1 lipids, which represents a 60-fold improvement over parental strain and conditions. Through this rewiring effort, we advance fundamental understanding of lipogenesis, demonstrate non-canonical environmental and intracellular stimuli and uncouple lipogenesis from nitrogen starvation. The high titres and carbon-source independent nature of this lipogenesis in Y. lipolytica highlight the potential of this organism as a platform for efficient oleochemical production. Â© 2014 Macmillan Publishers Limited. All rights reserved.</ce:para></abstract></dc:description><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/84892840633" rel="self"/><link href="http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=84892840633&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus"/><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/search/scopus?query=refeid%282-s2.0-84892840633%29" rel="cited-by"/></coredata><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60013372" id="60013372"><affilname>University of Texas at Austin</affilname></affiliation><authors><author auid="36175636700" seq="1"><ce:initials>J.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Blazeck J.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Blazeck</ce:surname><ce:given-name>John</ce:given-name><preferred-name><ce:initials>J.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Blazeck J.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Blazeck</ce:surname><ce:given-name>John</ce:given-name></preferred-name><author-url>http://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/36175636700</author-url><affiliation href="htt